President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring September 10-12, 2010, as National Days of Prayer and Remembrance in honor of the victims of the September 11, 2001 attacks. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of remembering those who lost their lives and expresses gratitude for the acts of valor and sacrifice displayed during and after the attacks. It also acknowledges the sacrifices made by members of the military serving in Iraq, Afghanistan, and elsewhere. The proclamation encourages Americans to honor the victims through various activities, including prayer, contemplation, memorial services, and visiting memorials. The president invites people around the world to participate in this commemoration.